{"allowedPrompts": [{"tool": "Bash", "prompt": "run docker compose build and tests"}], "plan": "# Plan: Strict Object-Level Authorization

## Context

The backend enforces role-based guards at the HTTP layer but performs almost no object-level ownership checks inside services. Any `staff_author` can update or delete sections/lessons belonging to another author's course. Any authenticated user can read version snapshots or approval details for courses they have no visibility into. Any `CourseAuthorGuard` user can submit another author's course for approval. These are IDOR vulnerabilities.

All authorization logic will be centralized in the **service layer** (not duplicated in routes). Routes pass `user_id`, `role`, and `department_id` down to services; services enforce the rules.

---

## Authorization Rules Reference

| Operation | admin | staff_author | dept_reviewer | faculty/student |
|-----------|-------|-------------|---------------|-----------------|
| Read sections/versions of course | always | own draft or any non-draft | dept match or published | published only |
| Mutate section/lesson | always | own course only | never | never |
| Submit course for approval | always | own course only | never | never |
| Read approval by UUID | always | own submission | same dept as course | never |
| Update/delete course | always | own draft/rejected | never | never |

---

## Changes

### 1. New Repository Helper — `course_repo.rs`

Add `find_section_by_id(pool, section_id: i64) -> Result<Option<CourseSection>, sqlx::Error>`:
```rust
pub async fn find_section_by_id(pool: &MySqlPool, id: i64) -> Result<Option<CourseSection>, sqlx::Error> {
    sqlx::query_as::<_, CourseSection>("SELECT * FROM course_sections WHERE id = ?")
        .bind(id).fetch_optional(pool).await
}
```
This is the only new repository function needed. All traversal is: lesson → `find_section_by_id(lesson.section_id)` → `find_course_by_id(section.course_id)`.

